Discover 5 unique access control devices

In this activity, I explored different types of access control devices used in everyday environments. These devices are used to restrict access to authorized users and improve security.

1. Keycard access (Unihall room)  
I used a keycard to access my room at UniHall. The card must be scanned on a reader to unlock the door, which ensures that only authorized residents can enter.

2. SmartRider card  
I used a SmartRider card on public transport. The card is scanned when entering the bus, which verifies payment and allows access to the service. This acts as an access control mechanism for transportation.

3. Fingerprint scanner  
I explored the fingerprint scanner on my laptop, which requires my fingerprint to unlock the device. This ensures that only I can access my personal data.

4. Facial recognition (Face ID)  
I used Face ID on my phone to unlock it. The system scans my face and compares it with stored data to verify my identity before granting access.

5. PIN-based access  
I observed the use of PIN codes in systems such as phones or ATMs. Users must enter a correct PIN to gain access, which restricts unauthorized use.

Overall, these devices demonstrate different methods of access control, including possession-based (cards), biometric (fingerprint and face), and knowledge-based (PIN). These methods help improve security by ensuring only authorized users can access systems or locations.
